    "suggested_edit": "In the 'Legal and Regulatory Challenges' section, after the paragraph on DSA proceedings and deceptive practices, add: 'On December 7, 2025, X terminated the European Commission’s advertising account following revelations that the EU had exploited X's ad system by disguising a promotional link as a video to artificially boost reach. X highlighted the irony, noting the EU fined X for alleged deceptiveness while employing similar tactics. This action escalates ongoing tensions amid DSA investigations and potential fines exceeding $1 billion. [new citation from tweet ID 1997462436476301430]'",
    "original_text": "The European Commission initiated formal proceedings against X under the Digital Services Act (DSA) on December 17, 2023, investigating potential breaches in risk assessment, content dissemination of illegal materials, and moderation of systemic risks like disinformation and hate speech. [199] Violations could result in fines up to 6% of X's global annual turnover, with reports in April 2025 indicating preparations for penalties exceeding $1 billion, alongside mandates for platform changes such as enhanced transparency in algorithmic recommendations and advertising. [200] [201] No outright ban has been imposed, but non-compliance risks service restrictions in the EU, a market comprising about 100 million users for X. [202]"
  },
  {
    "url": "https://grokipedia.com/page/Southwest_Airlines",
    "suggested_edit": "In the 'Regulatory Scrutiny and Fines' or 'Holiday Meltdown' section, after mentions of the $140 million DOT penalty and January 2025 lawsuit, append: 'On December 7, 2025, the Trump administration, via the Department of Transportation under Secretary Sean Duffy (former airline lobbyist), announced the waiver of the remaining fines against Southwest for the 2022 holiday meltdown and termination of the government lawsuit over chronically delayed flights. [new citation from tweet ID 1997436728987299853]'",
    "original_text": "On December 18, 2023, DOT imposed a record $140 million civil penalty on Southwest—the largest in agency history—for its December 2022 scheduling meltdown, which canceled over 16,900 flights and stranded passengers due to failures in crew scheduling software and inadequate contingency planning; Southwest also reimbursed passengers over $600 million in refunds and reimbursements as part of the resolution. [163] In January 2025, DOT filed a lawsuit against Southwest alleging chronic delays on two routes (Las Vegas to San Diego and Orlando to Aruba) exceeding federal tarmac delay rules, seeking civil penalties up to $37,377 per violation without admitting liability by the airline. [196]"
  },
