    "url": "https://grokipedia.com/page/Fl%C3%A1vio_Bolsonaro",
    "suggested_edit": "In the 'Future Ambitions and Presidential Runs' section, update or append: 'On December 7, 2025, Senator Flávio Bolsonaro announced his candidacy for the Brazilian presidency in the October 2026 election, stating: \"It is with great responsibility that I confirm the decision of Brazil’s greatest political and [context].\" This formalizes his positioning as a leading figure in the conservative movement amid family legal challenges. [new citation from tweet ID 1997023182016962915]'",
    "original_text": "Flávio has positioned himself as a potential standard-bearer for the movement, emphasizing the need for a 2026 candidate to secure pardons or amnesties for family members targeted by investigations, while critiquing leftist governance under President Lula da Silva. [53] Such efforts underscore a shared commitment to anti-corruption rhetoric—despite personal legal scrutiny—and economic liberalization, though Flávio's legislative focus has leaned more toward cultural conservatism than fiscal reforms. [54] As of early 2025, the case remains unresolved in federal courts, with Flávio facing ongoing indictment but no final conviction; he has referenced it as influencing his 2026 electoral strategy amid familial political constraints. [62] Flávio Bolsonaro admits indictment forces candidate shuffle for 2026. [62]"
  },
  {
    "url": "https://grokipedia.com/page/Donald_Trump",
    "suggested_edit": "In the 'Second presidency (2025–present)' section under economic policies or tariffs, append: 'On December 7, 2025, President Trump announced that tariff revenues could potentially eliminate federal income taxes, particularly for Americans earning under $200,000 annually, positioning tariffs as a funding mechanism to replace income taxes. This aligns with his protectionist agenda to boost domestic manufacturing. [new citation from tweet ID 1997341271548158274]' Also cross-reference the Southwest Airlines fine waiver under his administration.",
    "original_text": "In economic policy, Trump supports protectionism via tariffs to counter unfair foreign competition, including a proposed universal baseline tariff on imports and reciprocal rates matching those imposed on U.S. goods, aimed at revitalizing domestic manufacturing and addressing trade deficits exceeding $900 billion annually in recent years. The One Big Beautiful Bill Act, passed by Congress in 2025, extends most provisions of the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act—which reduced the corporate rate from 35% to 21% and individual rates across brackets—beyond their original expiration dates, alongside eliminating taxes on tips and overtime pay to boost worker incomes and curb inflation through deregulation and energy abundance."
